Report hath it that Prometheus stole the fire, and this tale says that Zeus flew into a rage and gave those who told him of the theft a charm to avert old age. I understand that the recipients of this charm put it upon an ass, and the ass went on before with his pack, and growing thirsty—for it was summertime -betook himself to a spring to get him drink. But the snake that guarded that spring checked his advance, aud would have driven him off had he not twisted his head about and bought his friendship with the only gift he had to hand, the charm he carried on his back. The bargain is struck. The ass drinks; the snake sloughs his old age, receiving, they say, the ass's thirst to boot. Well now; is this tale of my own making?
